<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0828-A"><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>Guests said she didn't attend.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041010.0447"><line>&quot;She said, 'It's going to be a riot up there if they treat her better than they treat us,'&quot; the visitor said, quoting the prisoner she was visiting.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>But the appeals brief argues that prosecutors and the trial judge kept the jury from understanding the difference.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041023.0038"><line>The prison allows her mother to have five books at a time, and she subscribes to newspapers, Alexis Stewart said.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="18"><scu uid="10" label="She read" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0375"><line>&quot;There is no freedom.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>Because gifts must be returned by prison officials, Stewart has asked fans to donate to the American Cancer Society instead.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>Stewart and Bacanovic had argued that they had a pre-existing agreement to sell the stock if the price dropped below 60 dollars a share.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>&quot;She's in very good spirits,&quot; said a source who spoke on the condition of anonymity.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>A Great Place to Spend Time.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>The lawyers also plan to argue that prosecutors improperly suggested during the trial that Martha Stewart engaged in insider trading, even though she was never charged with that crime.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="33"><scu uid="38" label="Stewart's lawyer has filed an appeal" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>Q. What will happen to the company, Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="13,32,57"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0375"><line>The lawyer said he did not know what she is writing, but Stewart has suggested since her conviction that she might write a book about her recent experience with the legal system.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="8" label="She writes" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041010.0447"><line>She's in good hands.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>An adviser to Bacanovic said he was considering doing so in order to get on with his life, but he is also planning to file an appeal and is free pending the outcome of that appeal.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>She said the American Cancer Society would keep a link on its Web site, www.cancer.org/makingstrides, that allows Martha fans to donate money via Stewart's team for about the next month.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>Walter Dellinger, the lawyer leading the appeal, said on NBC's &quot;Today&quot; that Stewart is exploring &quot;innovative ways to do microwave cooking&quot; with her fellow inmates.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>She has expressed &quot;great confidence&quot; in them and urged advertisers to stand by the company.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041010.0447"><line>US style guru Martha Stewart was friendly with inmates on her first night in jail and appeared in &quot;good spirits&quot; as she began serving a five-month prison sentence in West Virginia, US media reported Sunday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="5" sums="12,29,33,42,55"><scu uid="12" label="She made friends" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>As Martha Stewart arrives at the red-brick federal prison in Alderson, W.Va., on Friday to begin a five-month sentence, the company she founded is focused both on life without her and on life once she returns.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="10" sums="14,22,29,3,30,35,36,44,49,55"><scu uid="1" label="Martha Stewart was to serve a five-month sentence" weight="4"/><scu uid="3" label="Stewart was to serve her time at Alderson Federal Prison Camp" weight="3"/><scu uid="30" label="Her prison was in West Virginia" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>He argued that the judge erred by not separating his case from Stewart's.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>I have been told that some of these letters have included gifts and money.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>Stewart was charged only with deceiving investigators, not with insider trading.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>&quot;This is the first step in rebuilding her image,&quot; said Allen Adamson, managing director at Landor Associates in Manhattan.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>In a posting on her Web site, marthatalks.com, Stewart instead urged fans to make a donation to the American Cancer Society instead.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041010.0447"><line>Another woman who visited an inmate said some prisoners are worried the 63-year-old millionaire will get preferential treatment.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>Here are answers to some questions about the case:</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>The facility, which has no fences, has been dubbed &quot;Camp Cupcake&quot; by inmates, although detainees are expected to adhere to a strict regimen.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="48"><scu uid="31" label="Alderson was known as Camp Cupcake" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0375"><line>Because inmates can only use a microwave to do their own cooking, Stewart is working with fellow prisoners to &quot;come up with some creative recipes&quot; based on the limited number of ingredients available at the prison commissary, Dellinger said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>Waksal pleaded guilty to insider trading, admitting he sold ImClone because he knew about a forthcoming negative report about the company.</line><line>Bacanovic and Stewart were both given the option of staying out of prison while they appealed.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="20"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>If the package or letter is deemed inappropriate it will be returned.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0001"><line>&quot;I have adjusted and am very busy.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041010.0447"><line>The Alderson prison, which has around 1,050 inmates, sits in the Allegheny Mountains, some 270 miles (430 kilometers) southwest of Washington.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>&quot;We just wanted to see all the hoopla,&quot; said Bill Bright, 64.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041023.0038"><line>&quot;She was having a lot of fun playing Scrabble until I started beating her,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>When Stewart leaves prison and begins serving five months on house arrest, she will be allowed to work a limited number of hours per week.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>&quot;Instead, if you are so inclined, please make a donation to the American Cancer Society, a charitable organization that means a lot to me,&quot; she wrote.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>Some local residents have been taking advantage of the media circus surrounding Stewart's internment, selling T-shirts with tongue-in-cheek slogans like: &quot;West Virginia.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>Karen and Bill Bright of Buckhannon, W. Va., with cameras in hand, said they detoured 11 miles to take in the show.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0375"><line>&quot;What she likes best about it, I think, is how much she likes the fellow inmates and the people who run the prison facility at Alderson, and the respect that they all seem to have for each other,&quot; Dellinger said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0001"><line>Home fashion guru Martha Stewart said on Friday that she has adjusted to prison life and is keeping busy behind bars since reporting a week ago to a federal penal camp in West Virginia, where she is serving a five-month sentence for lying about a stock sale.<annotation scu-count="5" sum-count="6" sums="22,23,25,29,30,51"><scu uid="1" label="Martha Stewart was to serve a five-month sentence" weight="4"/><scu uid="22" label="She adjusted to prison" weight="2"/><scu uid="30" label="Her prison was in West Virginia" weight="2"/><scu uid="28" label="She kept busy" weight="1"/><scu uid="37" label="She was imprisoned for lying about a stock sale" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>She also says fans have sent her thousands of letters at Alderson, some including gifts and money.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0375"><line>She has no privacy.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>Lawyers for the celebrity homemaker argued in papers made public Thursday that government prosecutors, unchecked by the trial judge, confused jurors about the charges against Stewart.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0375"><line>Stewart is in the first month of a five-month sentence at the minimum-security federal women's prison in Alderson, West Virginia.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="4" sums="19,37,48,6"><scu uid="1" label="Martha Stewart was to serve a five-month sentence" weight="4"/><scu uid="3" label="Stewart was to serve her time at Alderson Federal Prison Camp" weight="3"/><scu uid="30" label="Her prison was in West Virginia" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0001"><line>Stewart, who reported to Alderson Federal Prison Camp before sunrise last Friday, said life at the camp held few surprises.</line><line>Stewart, 63, was convicted last March of lying to investigators about why she sold stock in a biotech drug maker in December 2001, just before its price plunged.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="37" label="She was imprisoned for lying about a stock sale" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>It has also purchased a magazine, Body &amp; Soul, and a newsletter, Dr. Andrew Weil's Self-Healing, which share similar health-related themes.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>Stewart will be issued four khaki work shirts, four khaki pants, two T-shirts, seven pairs of underwear, one pair of work shoes, one nightshirt, six pairs of socks and a coat.</line><line>&quot;I think the punishment exceeded the crime here, and I will be praying for her.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>The multimillionaire founder of the Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia lifestyle empire entered the minimum-security federal prison camp in Alderson, West Virginia at 6:15 am (1015 GMT), the Justice Department said in a statement.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="35"><scu uid="36" label="Stewart founded a multimillion-dollar empire" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>At her trial, prosecutors charged that Stewart was tipped off by her broker Peter Bacanovic to sell her ImClone stock in late 2001, just before a government announcement about an ImClone drug sent the share price plummeting.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="16,40"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>The letter states that &quot;Ms. Stewart has not abandoned her appeal&quot; and notes that while some materials had been turned over, &quot;they did not include any of the pretrial materials requested.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041023.0038"><line>Martha Stewart has been exercising, reading and making friends in prison, but the food at the minimum-security prison camp in West Virginia is &quot;terrible,&quot; the domestic diva's daughter said Friday.<annotation scu-count="5" sum-count="6" sums="0,13,20,43,49,7"><scu uid="7" label="She exercises in the gym" weight="3"/><scu uid="10" label="She read" weight="3"/><scu uid="12" label="She made friends" weight="2"/><scu uid="30" label="Her prison was in West Virginia" weight="2"/><scu uid="27" label="She thought the food was terrible." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0375"><line>Dellinger, who visited Stewart in prison Oct. 13, also said she performed sanitation chores, such as cleaning toilets.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="2" sums="10,37"><scu uid="11" label="She cleaned toilets" weight="2"/><scu uid="15" label="She did chores" weight="1"/><scu uid="16" label="She had visitors" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>But, she lamented, the gifts are not allowed to reach her.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>The company announced last month that she will be featured in a prime-time reality show produced by Mark Burnett, creator of &quot;Survivor.&quot;</line><line>On Thursday, Dellinger sent a letter to the U.S. attorney and the judge overseeing the case, demanding documents from the trial of Larry F. Stewart, an ink specialist who testified for the government and who was subsequently accused of perjury.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>Despite the prison's remote location -- nestled in the valley of the Keeney, Muddy and Wolf creeks and the Flattop Appalachian Mountains -- hordes of reporters and photographers have camped outside its stone and iron gates in hopes of recording Stewart's grand entry.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>The prison is no stranger to celebrity inmates, having housed the likes of jazz singer Billie Holiday, the would-be assassin of president Gerald Ford, Lynette &quot;Squeaky&quot; Fromme, and Kathryn Kelly, the wife of gangster &quot;Machine Gun&quot; Kelly.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041023.0038"><line>I'm not sure how much change they'd be willing to make,&quot; Alexis Stewart said on CNN's Larry King Live.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0375"><line>Homemaking mogul Martha Stewart is using her prison time to figure out &quot;innovative ways to do microwave cooking&quot; to share with fellow inmates and is being treated with respect, her lawyer said Thursday.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="7" sums="11,21,29,36,37,57,6"><scu uid="6" label="She created innovative microwave recipes" weight="4"/><scu uid="24" label="She was treated with respect" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>In the meantime, the statement said, &quot;Martha's standards of high quality and excellence will continue to guide everything we do.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>(c) 2004, Newsday=</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>And a jury in Manhattan acquitted Larry Stewart of perjury charges earlier this week.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>Before and after the trial, Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia suffered as television stations dropped her show, advertisers fled the bad publicity and circulation of the magazine fell.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041010.0447"><line>&quot;When she came in, she was in good spirits,&quot; a prison staffer told the New York Daily News.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>Laboratory files that tested ink notations on a document listing Stewart's stock holdings are among the materials sought by Stewart's lawyers.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>Concerned about Stewart's confinement, the Save Martha Web site has asked readers to send letters to Alderson's warden asking that Stewart be allowed to &quot;share her talents with other inmates so that something good can come out of this unfortunate situation.&quot;</line><line>Stewart, founder of a multimillion-dollar publishing and home-decorating empire, spent Thursday with her mother, Martha Kostyra, 90; daughter, Alexis, and sisters.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>Stewart is due to be released from prison in early March, and it is unlikely the appeals court will hear the appeal _ much less decide it _ by then.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>&quot;Alderson has a history of treating prisoners well,&quot; the source said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>Stewart, who was sentenced to five months of home confinement after her prison term, announced last month that she would begin serving her sentence without waiting for the outcome of an appeal she plans to file in the next few weeks.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>(c) 2004, Newsday=</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0375"><line>&quot;She has a group that is cooking,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>Stewart will complete the second week of a five-month prison term Friday for lying to the federal government about a stock transaction.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041010.0447"><line>Stewart reported to the jail on Friday to start a sentence for lying about a dodgy stock sale.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="18"><scu uid="37" label="She was imprisoned for lying about a stock sale" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>He also said she spends up to three hours a night writing on a typewriter.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>Stewart was an apparent no-show Thursday night for the wedding reception for Susan Magrino, her long time friend and publicist, at the Four Seasons restaurant in Manhattan.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>Stewart participated with her team in last year's walk, Marengo said.</line><line>During this year's walk, held last Sunday, Stewart's MSO team raised $31,000.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>&quot;She'll get more sympathy for being in West Virginia than she could get with all her high-priced lawyers.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>The trial judge has already rejected motions for a new trial based on the alleged lies by the juror and the ink expert.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>&quot;My lawyers remain very confident in the strength of my appeal and will continue to pursue it on my behalf,&quot; she said in her website message.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>&quot;She's making the best of what's necessarily a difficult situation,&quot; Dellinger said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>A. She was convicted in March of conspiring with her stockbroker to lie to federal investigators about why she unloaded shares of ImClone Systems stock in December 2001, just before the price plunged.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041023.0038"><line>The celebrity homemaker has not yet been assigned a job, but in the meantime she has been taking walks, going to the gym, watching television news and reading.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>Among them are allegations that a juror lied on his jury questionnaire and was biased against women, and that one of the government's own witnesses, ink expert Larry Stewart, lied on the stand.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>&quot;But please know this change is only an unfortunate reflection of my current circumstances, and in no way diminishes my commitment to my life's work or to the friends, colleagues, customers and supporters who make it possible,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>She is also entitled to a car and driver and a $100,000 &quot;nonaccountable expense allowance,&quot; the agreement states.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041010.0447"><line>Stewart, 63, was convicted in March of obstructing justice and making false statements to federal agents investigating her sale of nearly 4,000 shares in the biotechnology company ImClone Systems.</line><line>The New York Daily News said Stewart, wearing prison slacks, was spotted Saturday taking a midday stroll by herself on the grounds of the Alderson, West Virginia, federal prison.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0001"><line>&quot;The camp is fine; it is pretty much what I anticipated,&quot; she said in her Internet posting.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>Last month, however, Stewart asked to begin serving her time as soon as possible in order to put the &quot;nightmare&quot; of her criminal case behind her and &quot;reclaim my good life.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041010.0447"><line>She was treated just like anybody else, just like any inmate would be.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0375"><line>&quot;She is trying to figure out innovative ways to do microwave cooking which is all they have.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041023.0038"><line>Alexis Stewart described reports that she was being groomed to take over her mother's company, Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia, as &quot;a large exaggeration&quot; but the idea that she might someday run the company was within the realm of possibility.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>In the second quarter, the most recent results available, the company lost 39 cents a share.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>&quot;I don't think she knew what to expect, but she's certainly been very pleased about it.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>The company's share price has recovered to some extent, closing at $16.59 on Thursday compared with about $19 a share in June 2002, but the company has warned of losses through the end of the year.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>A spokeswoman for Stewart did not return calls for comment.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0375"><line>It's regimented.</line><line>They are subject to strip searches.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>&quot;She's very stoic,&quot; her main appeal lawyer, Walter Dellinger, said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0001"><line>The celebrity homemaker said she was touched by the outpouring of support she has received from millions of people who have visited her Web site, according to a letter posted by Stewart on www.marthatalks.com.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="33"><scu uid="13" label="She kept a website" weight="2"/><scu uid="19" label="She was touched by the support she received" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>The former Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. stockbroker has also asked the appeals court to overturn his conviction.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041023.0038"><line>&quot;Now she decided she doesn't want to play.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>The brief says prosecutors unfairly linked Stewart and ImClone founder Sam Waksal.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="25,51,57"/></line><line>Stewart and her former stockbroker, Peter Bacanovic, were each sentenced to five months in prison followed by five months of house arrest.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>The Alderson prison, which has around 1,050 inmates, sits in the Allegheny Mountains, some 270 miles (430 kilometers) southwest of Washington.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041023.0038"><line>Stewart said she had played Scrabble with her mother during her visits to the federal women's prison in Alderson, West Virginia.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="4" sums="0,20,43,7"><scu uid="3" label="Stewart was to serve her time at Alderson Federal Prison Camp" weight="3"/><scu uid="30" label="Her prison was in West Virginia" weight="2"/><scu uid="16" label="She had visitors" weight="1"/><scu uid="18" label="She played scrabble" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>Please know that while these gestures of friendship and support are deeply appreciated, any such items must be returned to the sender by prison officials.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>Bacanovic, who was tried and convicted along with Stewart and sentenced to a virtually identical punishment, has not announced plans to begin serving his sentence.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>In the meantime, Stewart's appeal attorneys accused government prosecutors Thursday of withholding evidence that could have led to an acquittal.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>Prosecutors told jurors that Stewart had received a &quot;secret tip&quot; about her ImClone Systems Inc. stock just before she sold in December 2001, and said the case was about &quot;cheating investors in the stock market.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>At the same time, Stewart is hardly relegated to the back burner.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>That judge has also written that &quot;overwhelming independent evidence&quot; supports the convictions.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>Stewart elected to begin doing her time, while Bacanovic remains free.</line><line>&quot;Martha Stewart was never charged with insider trading,&quot; the lawyers wrote, urging a federal appeals court to overturn her conviction.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="13,43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>She was convicted in March of lying to government investigators about the reasons for her sale of nearly 4,000 shares of ImClone Systems, a biotechnology company then run by her friend Samuel D. Waksal.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0375"><line>She appealed her conviction late Wednesday.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>She's anxious to really begin the closure.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>&quot;I continue to be touched by the outpouring of support I have received from so many of you,&quot; she wrote.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>She will begin serving a 5-month sentence for lying to federal investigators about her suspiciously timed stock sale.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>Q. Can she meet with her lawyers while she is in prison?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line><line>A. Stewart's lawyers hope to have the conviction overturned and must file their brief with the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals by Oct. 20.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0001"><line>&quot;The best news _ everyone is nice _ both the officials and my fellow inmates,&quot; the letter continued.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>Dellinger said he did not know what she is writing, but Stewart has hinted she may write a book about her experience with federal law enforcement.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="10,5"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>Stewart, whose net worth was estimated at nearly one billion dollars before her stock-selling scandal, will be designated work paying a maximum 40 cents an hour.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>Q. What is her appeals argument?</line><line>At Alderson, lawyers can visit during regular visiting hours _ 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. Fridays, Saturdays and Sundays, plus 8 a.m. to 3:30 p.m. on Mondays and holidays.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>Her role continues to be a complex one within the company, where employees look to her for guidance but saw their fortunes fade as her legal problems intensified in the last two years.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>A. Stewart, who resigned as CEO last year but has remained a guiding force in the company, now leaves it in the hands of its management team and board of directors.</line><line>Q. Stewart keeps saying she expects to be vindicated, but what are her chances?</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0001"><line>The camp is like an old-fashioned college campus _ without the freedom, of course.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>After she is released from prison, Stewart will also have to undergo five months of home confinement.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>There are no limits on the number of visits lawyers can make.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0375"><line>&quot;She's making the best of what's necessarily a difficult situation,&quot; lawyer Walter Dellinger said on NBC's &quot;Today.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>The notation &quot;60&quot; was central to the trial, because Stewart and her former stockbroker, Peter E. Bacanovic, both maintained that she sold her ImClone stock because they had earlier agreed to do so if the price fell below $60 a share.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0001"><line>The home fashion mogul is continuing to appeal her conviction.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>Neither publication includes Stewart's image or name, unlike the other products and publications the company distributes.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>American style guru Martha Stewart reported to a prison known as &quot;Camp Cupcake&quot; on Friday to start a five-month sentence for lying about a dodgy stock sale.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="4" sums="16,36,49,57"><scu uid="1" label="Martha Stewart was to serve a five-month sentence" weight="4"/><scu uid="31" label="Alderson was known as Camp Cupcake" weight="1"/><scu uid="37" label="She was imprisoned for lying about a stock sale" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>Her anticipated arrival has also attracted some tourists.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>&quot;But a barrage of pretrial leaks and in-court accusations left the indelible impression that she was guilty of that offense.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041023.0038"><line>Alexis Stewart said her mother has one roommate in a dormitory-type building that houses 80 women.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>Robert Kahn contributed to this story.</line><line>It also suggested that readers send care packages of craft items, snacks and board games &quot;that could help her pass the time.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041010.0447"><line>An inmate who met the businesswoman on her first night told her visiting aunt that Stewart was &quot;very friendly and very cordial,&quot; according to the New York tabloid.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>Since she reported to prison Oct. 8, Stewart has posted at least one letter on her personal-defense Web site saying that she is being treated well in prison.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="2" sums="20,21"><scu uid="13" label="She kept a website" weight="2"/><scu uid="24" label="She was treated with respect" weight="2"/><scu uid="32" label="She reported to prison on Oct. 8, 2004" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041010.0447"><line>&quot;She was received professionally.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>&quot;Send her my love,&quot; writer Dominick Dunne said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041010.0447"><line>She'll be fine.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041023.0038"><line>Martha Stewart, 63, who was convicted of lying to investigators about a stock sale, is serving a five-month sentence and is expected to be released in March.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="3" sums="32,41,43"><scu uid="1" label="Martha Stewart was to serve a five-month sentence" weight="4"/><scu uid="37" label="She was imprisoned for lying about a stock sale" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>However Zobel said inmate mail is subject to inspection for contraband or other banned items before it leaves the prison's postal facility.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>It was her decision to begin serving her term and hers alone.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>The appeals court will probably hear the case in early 2005.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0375"><line>But she's so resilient.&quot;</line><line>Stewart spends up to three hours a night writing on a prison typewriter with ribbons purchased at a prison store, he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>And reality TV show producer Mark Burnett has already signed on to refashion Stewart's lifestyle show and create other television projects around her once she's out of prison.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>He added, &quot;While the company can talk about planning for life without her, the best thing for the company is to get her back, get this done, and let her move beyond it.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>&quot;I am also touched that supporters have sent... thousands of letters to me.</line><line>Dawn Zobel, a public information officer at Alderson, said she could neither confirm nor deny that Stewart has been the recipient of such a tsunami of mail.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>The source said Stewart has no fears about her safety at the Alderson camp, the first federal prison for women in the country and nicknamed Camp Cupcake because of its bakery.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="19"><scu uid="31" label="Alderson was known as Camp Cupcake" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>Lawyers can also make arrangements with the prison to visit outside those hours.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>Stewart, 63, who rose from working-class roots in Nutley, N.J., to be named one of the United States' 50 Most Powerful Women by Fortune magazine in 1998, is expected to show up at the 105-acre, 1,040-inmate Alderson Federal Prison Camp in West Virginia by 2 p.m. EDT Friday.</line><line>In a letter to federal prosecutors, the lawyers alleged that documents and testimony of ink expert, Larry Stewart, showed the government lab had &quot;sabotaged&quot; testing of a key piece of evidence.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>Ana Marengo, a spokesman for the American Cancer Society in New York, said Stewart and her company Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia, have long had a team that participates in an annual walk in Central Park -- &quot;Making Strides&quot; -- to raise money for breast cancer research.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>A. Her lawyers have already outlined five main points they plan to make on appeal.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041010.0447"><line>She also saw two visitors, including her daughter Alexis.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>A. Legal observers say she faces an uphill battle.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>The style diva will be permitted to wear a watch valued at 100 dollars or less and a pair of earrings of similar value.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>The appeal is more about clearing Stewart's name, and about lifting the cloud of scandal that has hung over her company, Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia Inc., since the ImClone story broke in mid-2002.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>When Stewart was sentenced in July, the judge allowed her to remain free pending an appeal.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="40,6"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>Martha Stewart, trying to clear her tarnished name even as she serves a prison term, claims in her appeal that her trial was tainted by &quot;a barrage&quot; of unfair suggestions that she was charged with insider trading.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="21,43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>Larry Stewart, who is not related to Martha Stewart, was acquitted of the charges on Tuesday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="22,32,57"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>Q. Why is Martha Stewart doing time?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>Stewart, 63, was convicted in March of obstructing justice and making false statements to federal agents investigating her sale of nearly 4,000 shares in the biotechnology company ImClone Systems.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="40"><scu uid="37" label="She was imprisoned for lying about a stock sale" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>&quot;Losing all one's freedom and privacy for months is not an easy matter.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041021.0434"><line>The papers were filed as new details emerged about Stewart's daily life at the minimum-security federal women's prison in rural Alderson, West Virginia, her home until early March.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="3"><scu uid="3" label="Stewart was to serve her time at Alderson Federal Prison Camp" weight="3"/><scu uid="30" label="Her prison was in West Virginia" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041021.0145"><line>NEW YORK -- Martha Stewart says she has been deluged by &quot;thousands&quot; of letters from fans sent to her federal prison camp in Alderson, W.V., some of which have even included gifts and money.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="6" sums="11,14,37,41,44,6"><scu uid="14" label="She received many letters" weight="2"/><scu uid="30" label="Her prison was in West Virginia" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>A. Yes.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>&quot;With your good wishes in my heart, I am looking forward to being back at work in March, and to many brighter days ahead,&quot; she added.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041023.0038"><line>&quot;I'm sure she could give them quite a few pointers, but I think that the budget is so limited that...</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>Q. What happens next in the case?</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041008.0454"><line>&quot;While I am away, my updates here will be less frequent, if not altogether impossible,&quot; Stewart said in a message to supporters posted on her website.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041008.0329"><line>Martha Stewart, the American celebrity homemaker who had her own cooking and home improvement TV show, reported to a federal prison in Alderson, West Virginia, on Friday to serve a five-month sentence for lying about a stock sale.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="14" sums="10,11,12,13,14,23,25,3,30,35,41,42,44,51"><scu uid="1" label="Martha Stewart was to serve a five-month sentence" weight="4"/><scu uid="3" label="Stewart was to serve her time at Alderson Federal Prison Camp" weight="3"/><scu uid="30" label="Her prison was in West Virginia" weight="2"/><scu uid="37" label="She was imprisoned for lying about a stock sale" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>And she has signed a new contract that will pay her at least $900,000 a year, once her prison term is complete, and gives her the titles of founder, chief editorial director and media director.</line><line>The company, Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia, has already announced plans for a new television series that will start in January and will not include Stewart.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="22,55"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20041007.0172"><line>&quot;I think she is mentally prepared.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20041007.0274"><line>In a statement, the company called itself &quot;grateful for the closure that Martha's decision to serve provides the company,&quot; adding that &quot;We will miss her, and eagerly look forward to her return and to welcoming her back in March 2005.&quot;</line></document></collection>